"Poulsen C.J., Jeffery M.L.","Climate change imprinting on stable isotopic compositions of high-elevation meteoric water cloaks past surface elevations of major orogens",2011,"Geology","39","6",,"595","598",,,10.1130/G32052.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959249601&partnerID=40&md5=5f4016575f334c83ce25a2b7ca180dc3","Department of Geological Sciences, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, MI 48109-1005, United States","Poulsen, C.J., Department of Geological Sciences, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, MI 48109-1005, United States; Jeffery, M.L., Department of Geological Sciences, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, MI 48109-1005, United States","Stable isotope paleoaltimetry has been widely used to estimate Cenozoic surface elevation of major orogens. The infl uence of global climate change on stable isotope paleoaltimetry is uncertain, with proposals that warming could cause either overestimates or underestimates of past surface elevations. In this study we increase atmospheric pCO2 by two and four times in an isotope-tracking atmospheric general circulation model to investigate the effect of global warming on oxygen isotopic compositions of precipitation (δ 18Op) over the continents. As in other climate models, the response in the GENESIS version 3 model to global warming is an amplifi cation of upper troposphere temperatures through enhanced infrared absorption and a reduction in the surface to upper-level temperature gradient. Due to the temperature dependence of isotopic fractionation, vaporδ 18O (δ 18Ov) follows suit, leading to a reduction in the surface to upper troposphereδ 18Ov gradient. In regions of subsidence, including the major orogens and deserts, downward mixing of 18O-enriched vapor from the troposphere to the near surface further reduces the lapse rate ofδ 18Ov. As a consequence of these effects, the isotopic composition of precipitation in high-elevation regions, including the Tibetan Plateau, Rocky Mountains, European Alps, and Andean Plateau, increases by 3‰-6‰ relative to that at low elevations. Neglect of this climate effect on high-elevation δ 18Op has likely led to underestimates of the surface elevation of Cenozoic orogens. © 2011 Geological Society of America.",,"Atmospheric general circulation models; Cenozoic; Climate effects; European Alps; Global climate changes; Isotopic composition; Isotopic fractionations; Lapse rate; Meteoric waters; Near-surface; Orogens; Oxygen isotopic composition; Paleoaltimetry; Rocky Mountains; Stable isotopes; Stable isotopic compositions; Surface elevations; Temperature dependence; Temperature gradient; Tibetan Plateau; Upper troposphere; Arid regions; Global warming; Isotopes; Landforms; Troposphere; Vapors; Climate models; altimetry; atmospheric general circulation model; Cenozoic; climate effect; climate variation; global warming; isotopic composition; isotopic fractionation; meteoric water; paleoclimate; stable isotope; temperature gradient; troposphere; Alps; China; Qinghai-Xizang Plateau; Rocky Mountains",,,,,,"Blisniuk, P.M., Stern, L.A., Stable isotope paleoaltimetry: A critical review (2005) American Journal of Science, 305, pp. 1033-1074. , doi:10.2475/ajs.305.10.1033; Broccoli, A.J., Manabe, S., Mountains and mid-latitude aridity (1997), pp. 89-121. , Tectonic uplift and climate change: New York Ruddiman, W.F., ed., Plenum PressBrown, D., Worden, J., Noone, D., Comparison of atmospheric hydrology over convective continental regions using water vapor isotope measurements from space (2008) Journal of Geophysical Research, 113, pp. D15124. , doi:10.1029/2007JD009676; Dansgaard, W., Stable isotopes in precipitation (1964) Tellus, 16, pp. 436-468. , doi:10.1111/j .2153-3490.1964.tb00181.x; Dettman, D.L., Lohmann, K.C., Oxygen isotope evidence for high-altitude snow in the Laramide Rocky Mountains of North America during the Late Cretaceous and Paleogene (2000) Geology, 28, pp. 243-246. , doi:10.1130/0091-7613(2000)28<243:OIEFHS>2.0.CO;2; Ehl